**Concept:**

In the normal computation of factorial, we multiply the current factorial value by the next integer. However, because we are not allowed to use the multiplication operator, we simulate multiplication by using repeated addition. For example, to calculate fact×ifact \times ifact×i, we perform:

fact×i=fact+fact+⋯+fact⏟i&nbsp;times.fact \times i = \underbrace{fact + fact + \cdots + fact}_{i \text{ times}}.fact×i=i&nbsp;timesfact+fact+⋯+fact​​.**How It Works:**


Start with an initial factorial value of 111.
For every integer iii from 222 to NNN, simulate multiplication of the current factorial value with iii by adding the factorial value to a temporary variable iii times.
Update the factorial value and continue until NNN is reached.
**C++ Code Implementation (Approach 1):**

Below is the code following the given C++ template:

`#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int t;
    cin &gt;&gt; t;
    while(t--) {
        int n;
        cin &gt;&gt; n;
        int fact = 1;
        for (int i = 2; i &lt;= n; i++) {
            int temp = 0;
            for (int j = 0; j &lt; i; j++) {
                temp += fact;
            }
            fact = temp;
        }
        cout &lt;&lt; fact &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
