`**Concept:**

In this approach, we define a helper function `multiply(a, b)` that multiplies two numbers using repeated addition. Then, we compute the factorial recursively. The recursive definition of the factorial is:

N!=N×(N−1)!,N! = N \times (N-1)!,N!=N×(N−1)!,with the base cases 0!=10! = 10!=1 and 1!=11! = 11!=1. Each multiplication is performed by calling the helper function that adds the first number to itself bbb times.

**How It Works:**


**Helper Function**: `multiply(a, b)` iterates bbb times to sum aaa, thereby simulating the multiplication a×ba \times ba×b.
**Recursive Function**: The `factorial(n)` function calls itself recursively until reaching the base case. When returning from the recursive call, it multiplies nnn with the factorial of (n−1)(n-1)(n−1) using the helper function.
**C++ Code Implementation (Approach 2):**

Below is the C++ code following the template:

`#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt;
using namespace std;

int multiply(int a, int b) {
    int result = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; b; i++) {
        result += a;
    }
    return result;
}

int factorial(int n) {
    if(n == 0 || n == 1)
        return 1;
    return multiply(n, factorial(n-1));
}

int main() {
    int t;
    cin &gt;&gt; t;
    while(t--) {
        int n;
        cin &gt;&gt; n;
        cout &lt;&lt; factorial(n) &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
